One-to-Many Relationship (JPA / Database)
1. Foreign Key Location

The foreign key is always stored on the “Many” side.
Example:

Employee table contains dept_id (foreign key).
Department is the “One” side.




2. Foreign Key on Child Side Is Enough

As long as the child table has the FK column, the one-to-many relationship exists at the database level.
You do not need any special configuration on the parent side unless you want the relationship to be bidirectional.


3. Bidirectional Requirement

If you want both sides to access each other (Department ↔ Employee), then:

Parent (Department) must add a @OneToMany(mappedBy = "department").
Child (Employee) holds the FK with @ManyToOne.




4. Effect of Not Using mappedBy

In a bidirectional one-to-many, if mappedBy is not used:

JPA assumes you want a separate join table.
It creates a third table containing foreign keys of both sides.


This is usually not desired because one-to-many + join table = unnecessary complexity.